event_name: Klose to My Heart - Sonu Nigam Live in Concert
description: Sonu Nigam Klose to my Heart -The biggest Bollywood musical ever!Sonu Nigam - The Super Star, with his mesmerizing voice and enchanting lyrics, now live in concert with over 30 musicians.Experience 180 minutes of musical hypnosis. Sonu sings his favorite songs, from over the decade. Klose to my heart concerts have been enthralling people all over the world, and now Sonu Nigam brings it to India for the first time.It's a musical extravaganza that you just can't miss. The orchestra, with its full complement of string, percussion, brass and woodwind instruments, will perform in perfect unison with the versatile voice of the music maestro, SONU NIGAM…..With a magical and mesmerizing voice, Sonu Nigam is the epitome of an accomplished entertainer.Visit the three hour "KLOSE TO MY HEART" show by Sonu Nigam.

It’s a stand up comedy event in association with Round table India organized by Kolkata Spartans round table 280. Kenneth Sebastian, a famous stand up artist from Mumbai will tickle your funny bones with a breathtaking act and musical performance.25 year old Kenneth Sebastian is a Musician, Filmmaker and a Stand Up Comedian.Has performed in over 1000 shows in the last four years.He hosted & wrote an entire season of a Sketch Comedy Show ” The Living Room” which aired on Comedy Central India at primetimeSLOT in December 2014. Featuring established comedians such as Abish Mathew, Kanan Gill, Naveen Richard, Kaneez Surka & many more.He was featured as the number 1 young indian to watch out for in 2016 on Buzzfeed India. 1. Bollywood Night

Chitrahaar' is a Bollywood musical evening showcasing blockbuster hit songs of 60s, 70s, 80s and 90s. The show will feature some of the best and most remembered songs of the legendary singers of Bollywood.The event will feature a wide variety of evergreen hits ranging from melodious to mujra to foot-tapping numbers. Concept and lead singing - Samanvitha Sharma, who is an established, popular and celebrated singer in the cultural circuit of Bangalore.This exuberant musical evening will also showcase other noted singers of Bangalore Haris Karoth, Subrat Sahoo, Aniket Prabhu, Govind Kurnool and Rohini Prabhunandan. There will also be a full-fledged orchestra under the popular keyboardist Pradeep Patkar who hails from the Bollywood city of Amchi Mumbai.With a powerful blend of versatile music and artists, the event promises to be a real treat to the Bollywood music connoisseurs of Bangalore. This event will be held in aid of the 'Sri Ramachandra Grameena Vidya Vikasa Kendra Trust' which provides education to under-privileged children.'Chitrahaar' is a Bollywood musical evening showcasing blockbuster hit songs of 60s, 70s, 80s and 90s. Panchajanya, Nandikar's new musical, premiers! Please do join us as we embark on this new journey! Cast and Credit: Direction: Sohini Sengupta Drama, original score and co-direction: Parthapratim Deb Music design: Mayukh-Mainak Choreography: Debkumar Pal Sets: Debabrata Maity Lights: Sadhan Parui Styling and make-up: Md. Ali, Malay Das and Nripen Chakraborty Cast: Young actors of Nandikar and Swatilekha Sengupta, Rudraprasad Sengupta, Sohini Sengupta, Shambhu, Swajan Srijan, Sushanta and Parthapratim Deb Synopsis: The Kurukshetra War has just ended. Gandhari, after losing her hundred sons, is a much-grieved lady. She holds Krishna responsible for her misery. Radha asks Krishna why, despite being the most powerful person in India, Krishna cannot confide in anyone. Krishna tells his side of the story. As the story unfolds we see how Krishna, the young shepherd boy, is always trusted by people around him to be their savior. How every time it is Krishna who has to take a strong - and sometimes unpleasant - stand to ensure justice. How Krishna must sacrifice his personal life to free India from the hungry grip of Jarasandha and Kamsa in order to establish the rule of Dharma. How Krishna merely becomes an instrument of justice. How destiny takes over his life. But can Krishna, who has been the epitomic symbol of love, allow destiny to take away all that is tender in him? Can commitment to the State be greater than commitment to Humanity? How does a responsible man choose? Can a responsible man choose? Can war ever bring peace? Photographs and other info: http://facebook.com/nandikar

The next Maha Kumbh Mela will be held in Feb 2025 and I WILL be going. If you think thats something you would like to work on attending then you have twelve years to plan for it !! The Kumbh Mela is a massive festival where all religious sects come to the one place in Allahabad to wash their sins away on specific bathing days. Here you will see peoples that are normally very hard to get to and experience all kinds of yoga, meditation and amazing sights. Its a one off experience and normally there are approx 40million people that attend. I can organise luxury tents for us and get it all planned out once I know how many people might be interested. So please let me know and I will work out a good deal with contacts I have in India.

जलियांवाला बाग अमृतसर के स्वर्ण मंदिर के पास का एक छोटा सा बगीचा है जहाँ 13 अप्रैल 1919 को ब्रिगेडियर जनरल रेजीनॉल्ड डायर के नेतृत्व में अंग्रेजी फौज ने गोलियां चला के निहत्थे, शांत बूढ़ों, महिलाओं और बच्चों सहित सैकड़ों लोगों को मार डाला था और हज़ारों लोगों को घायल कर दिया था। यदि किसी एक घटना ने भारतीय स्वतंत्रता संग्राम पर सबसे अधिक प्रभाव डाला था तो वह घटना यह जधन्य हत्याकाण्ड ही था। 13 अप्रैल 1919 को बैसाखी का दिन था। बैसाखी वैसे तो पूरे भारत का एक प्रमुख त्योहार है परंतु विशेषकर पंजाब और हरियाणा के किसान सर्दियों की रबी की फसल काट लेने के बाद नए साल की खुशियाँ मनाते हैं। इसी दिन, 13 अप्रैल 1699 को दसवें और अंतिम गुरु गोविंद सिंह ने खालसा पंथ की स्थापना की थी। इसीलिए बैसाखी पंजाब और आस-पास के प्रदेशों का सबसे बड़ा त्योहार है और सिख इसे सामूहिक जन्मदिवस के रूप में मनाते हैं। अमृतसर में उस दिन एक मेला सैकड़ों साल से लगता चला आ रहा था जिसमें उस दिन भी हज़ारों लोग दूर-दूर से आए थे।

Jammu and Kashmir got hit by worst kind of flood in past 60 years, devastating of 2,500 villages and the cities of Jammu and Srinagar. Thousands of people lost their homes and are left with nothing. Many people lost lives and still thousands are missing, families are broken. Whole life in this himalayan valley is put on halt by the flood waters and washed away lands. Almost all the agricultural and horticultural crops have been washed away by the flood and destroyed completely. People are left with no food, drinking water and are struggling to find the shelter. Main Hospitals like the Children Hospital, only Maternity hospital of valley and Bone and Joint Hospital were worst hit and now the health sector is disfunctional to larger extent. All the communication channels have been broken, the road have been washed away by flood waters and whole valley is disconnected from the rest of world. The after affects are flood might be worse as whole life has been badly shaken in the valley. In absence of health care, lack of food and drinking water, poor infrastructure, broken land communication it seems a tough task to get life back on track. So our aim is to reach out to the people in need at this tough time and provide them support just for the noble cause of humanity. description: The weather is exactly right to get down and get your hands {and clothes} dirty. Wet clay, artistic expression, pretty pottery—all in an idyllic environment with sprawling lawns, towering trees, flowering shrubs and lotus-ponds. You'll be taught by our renowned master artisan.Who Is It For? Anyone above 18 years can try his or her hand at this fun, relaxing art form. Children above the age of 6 years are welcome, as long as a parent accompanies them.You could be an absolute beginner looking for a brand new hobby or a seasoned potter; this should be fun for everyone. Why Should You Go For It?You’ll learn hand-building techniques of working with clay, working on the potter’s wheel {called throwing} and decoration techniques.In addition, you get to explore the Sanskriti Terracotta Museum, the Crafts Museum. The package also includes a complementary refreshment. Do wear clothes you’re not afraid to get dirty as pottery is inevitably messy. If you have children, take them along. And you get to take what you make home! For any help, WhatsApp/call us at +91 750 341 9644 or email us at ptahworkshops@gmail.comNote: Additional charges of Rs.150 (can be paid on the workshop day) for the refreshments for the parent(s) accompanying their kid(s) but not participating.About the Artist:Santosh Kumar, a proponent of the tradition, teaches the craft at schools and is known for adapting, innovating and incorporating changes in the profession.• Participated in several events & workshops across India• His work has been exhibited at many prestigious art galleries & exhibitions in IndiaAbout the Venue:The Sanskriti Kendra is the Foundation’s Cultural Centre located in an idyllic natural environment with sprawling lawns, towering trees, flowering shrubs, lotus-ponds, homes to birds and butterflies (Nature at Sanskriti). It serves as conducive space for innovative and interactive work.For more information visit http://www.sanskritifoundation.org/kendra.htmAbout the Workshop:Pottery/terracotta, the ancient tradition traces back to the earliest civilisation of India. Pottery is one of those important mediums through which men have expressed their emotions. For thousands of years pottery art has been one of the most beautiful forms of expression. A piece of pottery has a visual message in its shape and colour.Potteries can be both handmade and wheel-made, which is practised all over India.

event_name: Roopa Viroopa - A Tale Of True Love
description: Roopa viroopa, a take off from the famous fairy tale beauty and the beast speaks of a true love bewteen a beautiful village lass and an ugly beastly looking tribal, who s actually a very handsome prince , cursed to become so due to his conciet. What follows is a series of emotional dramas which leave us wondering , wil l they actually unite? India is truly blessed to have its most treasured asset, the indian classical dance idioms. The temple dances have stood strong for more than a thousand years owing to their deep historical , mythological and spiritual connects.. Although many have notions about the classical art forms being confined to a nut shell, boundary , limitations etc, peole are yet to explore how the same can also create one of the best modes of entertainment , and that is the sole aim of shivapriya school of dance. The dance school is popular in adapting challenging fairy tales to our indian format and has been successful in prresenting them to full houses in srilanka, america , the middle east and singapore.. Roopa viroopa is one among them, having received a satnding ovation , owing to its soul stirring music, beautiful choreographic blends of indain calssical and folk dance forms, high elements of theatre and drama ( with power packed english dialogues and narrations ) vibrant costumes, multimedia , humor, etc all appealing to people of all ages. The brain child behind this production , dr. Sanjay , has nearly 30 string years of experience as an actor / dancer / musician / choreographer and start creator.Why the event ----Alongside its service to the community through teaching, propogating dance, shivapriya has been supporting several charitable organisations in its best possible way and this time intends to support -- nandana, a shelter for children suffering from various mentally challenging illnesses such as cerebral palsy, down s syndrome, etc. The shelter takes innate effeorts to take care of all these abandoned kids with a limited staff and has been successful in running the novel task since many years despite several challenges. We appeal to you to kindly purchase as many tickets as possible to help us support this organisation and also savour the essence of the beautiful, production which is of a duration of 75 minutes. The event is scheduled to happen on sunday, the 19 th of june, at ada rangamndira, j.c road, bengaluru .as the number of seats are limited, we request you to purchase your nominally priced ticket at the earliest. Looking forward to your kind gesture and love for the arts. Language: kanada/englishGenre: indian classical dance form – bharathanatyam/ theatre / kuchupudiAge guidance: age above 5 years

“Writing, Acting, Directing, Stage” Theater or Drama is popularly known for this. But there is more to it.There are strong elements of make-believe in all children’s play. This make-believe helps the child to test out his/her hypotheses about what the world is like and how it might feel to have certain experiences. It is fuelled by inquisitiveness and a desire to think about possibilities and concepts through the medium of action. The process by which this is done is the same process as that by which drama is made for all levels and ages.We meet drama most frequently in the theatre, on television or in the cinema, and we associate it with performance, costumes, setting and stages. Similarly, in the club we often associate drama with script, rehearsal, voice production and the display of acting talent. This type of drama has certain benefits in that; it increases children’s self-confidence, gives them the opportunity to express themselves in public and allows them the opportunity of appearing on stage. However, it represents only a part of the rich learning and developmental experience that drama has to offer.Drama is a holistic activity and it is difficult to separate the form from the content, the affective from the cognitive, the social development from the personal. Nevertheless, it can be said that its educational outcomes derives from two sources:The knowledge and insights gained from bringing the child’s experience to bear on the examination of a particular aspect of life through dramaThe personal skills, social skills and drama skills that must be encouraged if the class is to enter effectively into and create the world of the drama.Aims of the Drama ClubTo enable the child to become drama literateTo enable the child to create a permanent bridge between make-believe play and the art form of theatreTo develop the child’s ability to enter physically, emotionally and intellectually into the drama world in order to promote questing, empowering and empathetic skillsTo enable the child to develop the social skills necessary to engage openly, honestly and playfully with othersTo enable the child to co-operate and communicate with others in solving problems in the drama and through the dramaTo enable the child to understand the structures and modes of drama and how they create links between play, thought and lifeTo enable the child to begin the process of translating the knowledge of drama into the active exploration of life themes from drama literature, leading to the appreciation of world drama cultureTo form the criteria with which to evaluate the drama texts, written or performed, to which he/she is continually exposed.Role of the Drama FacilitatorThe primary task of the drama facilitator is to preserve and encourage the desire to make-believe while at the same time extending it to other areas of life and knowledge. In this way drama can assist in the fulfillment of the child’s current cognitive and affective needs and in providing for his/her future personal, social, emotional and intellectual development.Overview of the contentWe will explore various elements of drama in the program.We start the sessions by understanding and exploring basic techniques of theatre.We will explore elements like speech, body language, voice modulation etc.Later we will explore much deeper elements like character building, role, tension, interaction between characters, stage ethics, genre etc.Structure of the Drama ClubDuration: 10 Days (1 and a half hour every day)Age Group: (Minimum number of students: 8 / Maximum Number of students: 20)7 yrs to 12 yrs

The 5th Edition of K-Pop Contest –India 2016 is all set to thrill Indian K-Pop fans. Delhi K-pop fans will have their auditions on Saturday 25th June 2016 at Korean Cultural Centre, Lajpat Nagar, New Delhi. The auditions will start at 04:30 P.M. one can witness the thrilling dance and Song competition on this day. This time we haveEddy and Simba – the celebrity judges from JJCC Band (Jackie Chan Group Korea), K-POP idol group IMFACT, Davis Kim - South Korean-Americansolo singer-songwriter, Hayana a solo artist in our judge’s panel at different rounds.This year the grandeur and craze of K- POP will be seen in Delhi, Kolkata, Bangaluru, Patna, Mumbai, Chennai and Sikkim with its finale in Chennai on 30th July 2016. K-POP idol group IMFACT will be the judges for the regional round in Sikkim while K-POP Singer/Songwriter Dabit along with Solo artist Hayana will be the judge for the regional rounds in Kolkata and Bangalore.The winners from the regional round will get an all-expenses paid trip to compete for the Grand Finale in Chennai. The winning team at the grand finale will be awarded all expenses paid trip to South Korea, sponsored by Korean Cultural Centre (KCCI). The winning participants will also be nominated for the Changwon K-pop World Festival.In addition to the K-Pop contest, Indian K-Pop fans will get the opportunity to witness a mini-concert / fanmeet of popular K-Pop group JJCC on 31st July, 2016. The mini-concert will be organized by Pink Box Events in association with Korean Cultural Centre. For more details, you can check the event page at www.facebook.com/PinkboxeventsInformation on Term and Conditions to participate in K-POP 2016 India festival is available on www.kpopindia.comFor more details, please contact:koreanculturalcentreindia@gmail.com011 43345000 /011 43345033 BRIEF ABOUT K-POPK-pop India contest comes under the banner of K-POP World festival organized by South Korea’s Ministry of Foreign affairs. India is pacing fast with the Hallyu wave (Korean entertainment and Pop culture) with other 70 countries participating every year. Korean Pop most commonly known as K-POP is a musical genre originally from South Korea, characterized by a wide variety of audio visual elements, the term is more often used in a narrower sense to describe a modern form of South Korean pop music covering mostly dance-pop, pop ballad, electronic, rock, hip-hop, R&B, etc. The craze and the jazz for this genre of music are extremely popular and global. The concept of K-POP idols brought an interesting change in the rise of Hallyu wave globally.In India, K-POP has been rising at a rapid rate ever since the Gangnam style era, a genre which was mostly followed in North Eastern part of India has now become teenagers favourite genre across the country. K-POP Contest provides a unique platform for all to prove their mettle in Korean singing and dancing.ABOUT Imfact BandImfactis aSouth Koreanboy bandunder Star Empire Entertainment formed in 2016. Their debut mini-albumLollipopwas released on January 27, 2016.Before debuting, they performed at the K-Pop Contest 2015 India Grand Finale in New Delhi, India. They gained popularity in India quickly which sped their debut date and since they have a large fan following in India, they have been invited once again to perform in Sikkim. About JJCC BandJackie Chan Joint Culture also known as JJCC, is a South Korean hip-hop boy group formed by Jackie Chan Group Korea which is owned by internationally acclaimed Chinese actor Jackie Chan. The group debuted in March 14, 2014. Their debut single ‘At First’ was then released on March 24. JJCC is the first K-pop idol group to be formed by Jackie Chan. The name of the band is composed of the man who forms the group and the group's aim. The first "JC" comes from the first letters of the words Jackie and Chan while the second "JC" comes from the first letters of the words join and cultures. When combined together, it is literally "Jackie Chan Joint Cultures" (JJCC) translated to "Jackie Chan, let's spread K-Pop". In the same way, the pronunciation of the group name (Double-JC) stands for "Double Joy Creative" or "Let's create double the joy”. The band name is a tribute to Chan as well as his effort to "join cultures" in Asia through music.About Singer Davis KimDavid Kim better known by his stage name Dabitis a South Korean-American solo singer-songwriter under Koffee Dream Management (KDM). He debuted on his birth date, December 5, 2013. His fan club name is called "Dalbit" which means "moonlight". He was born and raised in the state of Ohio. About Artist HayanaHayana is a solo artist who debuted as a part of 5 member K-Pop girl group EvoL from South Korea under the label Stardom Entertainment. Currently she is a solo artist under Koffee Dream Entertainment.

Based on his own narrative poem Parishodh (1899), Tagores Shyama (1939) is a major dance-drama. A tragic story that tells us about lust, love, betrayal and remorse - Shyama portrays the eponymous heroine of the piece - a danseuse of the royal court - who falls in love with Bajrosen, a foreign merchant wrongfully convicted of theft and condemned to death. In order to save Bajrosen's life,Shyama coaxes her young admirer Uttiyo to pose as the thief which gives the final reprieve to Bajrosen. After a brief period of euphoric love-making with Shyama following his release, Bajrosen learns to his dismay how he had been saved in exchange of an innocent life and decides to disown Shyama on a moral ground in spite of his deep love for her. The piece ends in a conradian crisis, where the bigger moral question is evenly poised against love and desire.Performers:Soumili Biswas, Sreela Majumdar, Sabyasachi Chakraborty, Satinath Mukherjee, Sraboni Sen, Pramit Sen, Debadrito Chatterjee, Surojit Biswas, Susmita Gupta, Arnab Bandyopadhay

Phera adapted by Shri Soumitra Chatterje from Freidrich Durrrenmatt's 'The Visit' is not just the story of a girl wronged, who returns to seek vengeance. It would be wrong to limit its interpretation to such a basic format. It is an important statement on the socio-economic situation of the state, in fact the whole country. Money can buy almost everything is a sad truth in our country and even more so at present times. The depth of poverty and at the same time the temptations that are constantly being flashed before the eyes of the marginal section is tearing down the moral fabric of society as a whole.This is the idea that is established in the play through the story of Pratima Singha who comes back to her native village Bonpahari after almost thirty years. Bonpahari is a village which is struggling to stay alive on a dole provided by the government, a village so backward and poverty stricken that the people can only wait for a miracle to save them from the depths of utter despair. The miracle comes in the form of Pratima Singha who promises to help them out but on one condition. The condition being that the villagers have to kill Kashinath, her former lover who had jilted her when she was pregnant and as a result she had been forced into prostitution. The villagers are initially aghast at such a proposal and reject Pratima's offer outright. But Pratima having conquered the world knows that it is only a matter of time before the desperate desire to survive and live a better life will slowly change the will and the mental makeup of the villagers. Kashinath is helpless against their greed and their survival instinct and is ultimately killed. Pratima who had already become cold, inhuman and devoid of any moral values kills herself and falls beside Kashinath. This need to exact vengeance which had kept her alive and sustained her throughout these years is now no more. The play ends with their death but raises many questions. Questions which point fingers at our socio-economic structure as a whole. Why in the first place did Pratima have to pay such a huge price for her love which ultimately destroyed so many souls and exposed the helplessness, the greed, the corruption, the darkness of our social fabric?DIRECTOR:Poulomi BoseARTISTS: Soumitra Chatterjee, Debshankar Haldar, Poulomi Bose, Subrata Samajdar, Anirban Chakraborty, Debnath Chatterjee, Debdas Ghosh, Kunal Karmakar, Debabrata Maity, Priyanath Mukherjee, Rajat Mallick, Prosenjit Bhattacharya, Riddhibhesh Mukherjee

National performing arts company, M.A.D (Mad About Drama) brings for you the 3rd edition of THE MADHOUSE WORKSHOP SERIES- a one of a kind 2 day workshop series for performing artists.Categories:1. Acting for camera & stage2. Direction & scripwritingAge group : 15yrs to 50yrs.Dates : 11th June (Saturday) & 12th June (Sunday)Schedule :11th June(sat) & 12th June(sun) : 10am to 2pm (Acting)11th June(sat) & 12th June(sun) : 3.30pm to 7pm (Direction and Scrip writing)About the workshops:ACTING FOR CAMERA AND STAGE:The acting workshop will explore different approaches to acting and the importance of using the mind and body, to feel and express. Reading and analysing a script and building a character based on character motivation will be attempted. Stanislavski's magic 'What if' and Lecoq's 'Levels of Tension' will be applied to act out scenes. The subtle and not so subtle differences between the screen and stage will also be explored. The workshop will be industry relevant so that the participants are quite well equipped at the end of two days to carry themselves in a professional space.DIRECTION AND SCRIPTWRITING:The writing and direction workshop will attempt to understand the nuances of writing/directing a play from the point of view of a performing artist in the 21st century. It will delve deep into the works of path breaking directors like Thomas Ostermeier, Robert Wilson, Tim Supple and Simon Mcburney and will look at the works of contemporary playwrights such as Ayad Akhtar, Sarah Kane and Christopher Durang. It will try and explore how the international language of performance has changed by trying to link older masters and older texts with modern interpretations of the same. It will look at every little aspect from framing and composition to designing character arcs using examples as varied as Heiner Mueller and Peter Brook. It will also look at works of playwrights such as Manjula Padmanabhan and Mahesh Dattani closer home to specfically locate an "Indian" language of performance that has evolved over the years. It will also attempt to understand the technical aspects associated with writing material for allied mediums ranging from youtube sketches and songs to radio plays. It will try to identify methods through which full fledged story ideas are developed into scripts, covering every stage from concept writing to pitching. The workshop will be hands on and interactive to make sure it's not just a theoretical discussion, but also a practical exercise in creating and executing original material.*Please note that the registration fees is for BOTH the days.Not on per day basis.

Sadhin Das, a poor Saree Vendor from Shorshe, West Bengal comes to the Court of Law demanding justice. From a long time now, he has been suffering from a strange optical disorder! RED and GREEN are the only colours visible to his eyes! The play puts forward the present day picture of the political influence that can affect a man, a community and can transform his vision, mearly reducing him to a machine, amachine which can give votes! Come, witness and question yourselves, is this the democracy we're so proud of? Is this freedom? Freedom of vision?Directed By: Chandan Sen

The 1950s. India is Independent. Bengal cut in two (East and West) is trying to survive the severing of ties many centuries old – of languages, lives and loves.The blood that flows is red on this side and that, the moon still rises on this side and that. Yet people fly miles away from home in search of shelter. And the child cries alone in the dark…‘Jaadubangsho’, boldly faces the problems of a tumultuous time. As in all Manoj Mitra plays the brilliant comedy touches issues relevant to all times - childlessness, fellow feeling, homelessness and the godlike magic everyman can perform.Jadugopal’s business in timber and handmade furniture flourishes in North Calcutta, but he is easygoing, even childish. Wife Nandorani blames his laidback attitude for the fact that they are still without a child. Frantic in grief Nandorani devotes all her time to rituals in the hope that an heir is born to them, even though both husband and wife are well past their prime. With them stay Jadu’s brother Narugopal who is a Jatra proprietor rendered out of work because of the violence and restrictions that came with Partition and Fagun, the daughter of an employee from East Pakistan who has taken shelter from the mayhem all around.Dhurjoti a distant relative of Jadugopal looks after a grand farm house inherited by Nandorani. Dhurjoti who looks the perfect gentleman is a thief unlike Sanai who though jailed for robbery is not a thief. The two meet one night when a group of refugees are looking for a lost child

The theme portrays the condition of women in our soceity,which still remains a burning social issue of India.In the storyline we decided to delve into our myths and legends and from them we chose some characters whose lives manifest the essence of womanhood.Starting from the Rajput queen Padmini,we traverse a path carrying us to Draupadi and her plight,to Mumtaz Mahal and her story behind the erection of the Taj Mahal,to Sita and her trials through fire,to the 1989 Sati of Roop Kanwar, we finally come to the contemporary soceity,and question all that has there really been a change in the condition of women.I thought to uphold a social cause through dance,so that the soceity thinks twice before disrespecting a woman. This production will be presented by my troupe of classically trained dancers on the 18th of June,2016 at Mahajati Sadan.The script has been written by Sri Ratan Kr Das,music will be composed by Dishari Chakraborty. Eminent personalities like Dr. Guru Smt. Thankamani Kutty, Mr. Goutam Halder, Mr.Biplab Chatterjee, Ms. Alakananda Roy, Ms. Mamata Shankar, Ms. Swagatalaxmi Dasgupta, Mr.Sounak Chatterjee and many others will be present at the program.

Directed by PRITHUNANDAN GHOSEMajor characters are portrayed by eminent actors like Sudip Mukherjee, Shyamal Chakraborty, Bindiya Ghosh, Prabir Dutta, Kinjal Nanda and legendary Indian football star Surojit SenguptaDescription :The story, told by a narrator, through his mesmerizing songs, weaves round an urban family and its neighbourhood. An evening of spectacular works of ace choreographer, actor and Dancer Padmashri Shobana. Crafted for lovers of avant-garde, innovative and classical and Bollywood dancing, the musical showcases Krishna - The man, his philosophy and why he is still beyond man's understanding.Whenever righteousness fails and evil rears its ugly head, the supreme releases himself in this world. He takes ten incarnations in Indian mythology and the musical 'Krishna' is about the ninth incarnation of the lord. All on a canvas from Vrindavan and Mathura to Kurukshetra This first-of-its-kind world class musical is a joyous collage of music, dance, dialogues and delightful costumes and voicevovers of leading film actors like Surya, Konkona Sen Sharma, Shabana Azmi, Andrea Jeremiah and Prabhu, to name a few. The musical has witnessed standing ovations in more than 80 cities across 30 countries. Be there to witness the 85th staging of the Icon Krishna on an auspicious day (Janmashtami).

Summer is the perfect time for you to help your tiny tots discover their hidden talents, especially with all that free time on their hands. If you agree, join our Paper Revolution today with one of our paper toy making workshop! The workshops have been designed to give you the know-how to create all sorts of awesome stuff with paper – and wherever possible we encourage you to Reuse, Reinvent and Recycle. Who Is It For?Kids who’re above five years of age & Adults both (Children below the age of 16 yrs should be accompanied by adults.). It’s the perfect opportunity for kids who want to either hone their existing skills or pick up some new ones.Why Should You Go For It?Mouse, Tortoise, giraffe, squirrel, butterfly....give any beautiful shape to paper. You’ll be provided with all the material and brilliant templates to create your personalized stuffs. Just fold them out, cut glue and enjoy!In addition, you get to explore the Sanskriti Terracotta Museum, the Crafts Museum. The package also includes complementary snacks and high tea.Note: Additional charges of Rs.300 (can be paid on the workshop day) for the snacks & high tea for the parent(s) accompanying their kid(s) but not participating.For any enquiry, WhatsApp/call us at +91 750 341 9644 or email us at ptahworkshops@gmail.comKnow the Venue:The Sanskriti Kendra is the Foundation’s Cultural Centre located in an idyllic natural environment with sprawling lawns, towering trees, flowering shrubs, lotus-ponds, homes to birds and butterflies (Nature at Sanskriti). It serves as conducive space for innovative and interactive work.For more information visit http://www.sanskritifoundation.org/kendra.htmKnow the Artist:Sanjeev Kumar Chouhan knows the art of amusing children and even adults with his colourful paper toys in fascinating shapes and sizes. From the early age of 11, he had great fascination for paper toys, and he chose to make his hobby a livelihood.He has also been teaching a large number of teachers and students at the Centre for Cultural Resources and Training. He has made a number of games for children at the National Bal Bhavan & been featured in the popular series ‘M.A.D.’ on POGO channel.

Sayak presents Passing Show. Based on the story of Amar Mitra. Playwright : Ujjal Chattapadhyay. Directed by: Meghnad Bhattacharya.Sayak’s New Play : PASSING SHOWSynopsis :The plot revolves around the frantic search of Atin – search for the fragrance of the golden past , old classics, vintage memoirs and music reaches a climax in his obsessive pursuit through time to find the singer, Atulananda, who recorded a song written by his father, Dhurjoti Dutta. His journey towards ‘time past’ necessitates the presence of a character who will link the present and the past. Ghulam Mohammad does exactly that by winding back the defunct gramophone to take the audience to the world of classics. The conflict ensues as the present material world interjects its mercantile value systems into the world of classical humanism and innocence. Ghulam with a shake of his hand takes us on a roller coaster ride, riding back and forth into past and present simultaneously as the conflict mentioned before makes its presence felt in Atin’s domestic life. This is established in the form of the tussle between him and his family members who want to refurbish their old house into modern apartments but as per Ghulam’s belief nothing in this world can be completely lost. Everything remains immortal in the aesthetic space of creation. And indeed Atin witnesses his father sitting in the corners of his old house. Roaming from one space to another, Atin ultimately finds the singer’s house and his son, Jibanananda, who has carefully preserved his father’s record till date. The theatrical proficiency doesn’t end here; a layer of mystical meta-theatre is added as Atin’s supposed ‘Other’ comes to visit him often. With the plot somewhat resolving it’s initiated conflicts with the meeting of Atin and Jibananda, Atin hopes to finally meet his ‘Other’. The curtain falls with this awkward expectation evoked.

AIM for SEVA presents 'Antar-Yatra'Choreographed and directed by Sharmila Biswas, of the Odissi Vision & Movement Centre, Calcutta, this dance-drama will tour seven cities (Chennai - Pune - Mumbai - Kolkatta - Delhi - Bangalore - Bhuvaneshwar) .Sharmila Biswas, Lakshmi Parthasarathy Athreya, Amrita Lahiri and Shashwati Garai Ghosh enlighten us on the temple dance traditions. Using Odishi, Bharathnatyam and Kuchipudi, the performers attempt to capture the soul of women dancers of India, from the past to the present. The theme of the dance production for this year is ‘Temple Dance Traditions’. Apasara, the celestial dancers, occupy a major space in Indian mythology. The temple dancers, the court dancers and other professional dancers of the past consider themselves the incarnations of the Apsaras. They have the privilege of knowing the sixty-four Kalas. They are the Vidyadharis. They exist simultaneously in the mystic and the real worlds. They engage in intimate dialogue with the abstract, and bring the essence of it to the common man. Using Odishi, Bharathnatyam and Kuchipudi, the performers attempt to capture the life and the artistic vision and the inner domain of the women dancers of India, from the past to the present.

event_name: Korean Cultural Centre, India presents Floral Art Exhibition at its centre.
description: Korean Cultural Centre, India in Association with Korea Flower Design Association, (India) is organizing Taewa Flower Arrangement Exhibition at Korean Cultural Centre, India based at Lajpat Nagar, New Delhi.Through the materials of floral art, Floral Art artists express their belief or outlook on the world and the way they polish one’s mindset and cultivate virtue in them. The thoughts and inner world are to be presented based on the spirit and righteousness of the artists who create the floral art work.Floral Art artists form expressions of floral art which is to be ‘intuitive’ and ‘dynamic’ and it tends to be more free-spirited. They deliver a beauty with aspects of being ‘simple’, ‘natural’ and ‘emotional’ that erupt from the human sensitivity.The mind that cherishes the flowers, trees and plants around us has become a part of people daily life. And it has been communicated with nature as well as with people. It also has become the continuous source of inspiration. The outcome of the floral artwork is not just its artistic value but it also includes the process of its creation along with the material, space and audience included in its formation and display. A close communication with these subjects brings in a good harmony among the artists and audience.

Synopsis:Set in the years between 1884 and 1899, this play follows the iconic Dr. Mahendralal Sarkar, a man steadfast in his ideals and never shy of speaking his mind, who dreams of founding a ''Science Association'', where women could embrace the medical profession and take care of their own illnesses. He is dispirited and cuts a sorry figure when his dreams are shattered, until he meets Ramakrishna Paramahansa and a transformation takes place. The play ''The Unsaid'' tries to chronicle a few chapters from the tale of this transformation, where the untold stories of some of the characters help to kindle hope and inspiration. This production attempts to find light at the end of a dark tunnel.Cast: Bimal Chakraborty, Jayanta Mitra, Debasish Chatterjee, Monjima Chattopadhyay, Sushmita Pan, Apurbo Saha, Kinjal NandaDirector:Seema Mukhopadhyay.

Sayak presents Passing Show. Based on the story of Amar Mitra. Playwright : Ujjal Chattapadhyay. Directed by: Meghnad Bhattacharya.Sayak’s New Play : PASSING SHOWSynopsis :The plot revolves around the frantic search of Atin – search for the fragrance of the golden past , old classics, vintage memoirs and music reaches a climax in his obsessive pursuit through time to find the singer, Atulananda, who recorded a song written by his father, Dhurjoti Dutta. His journey towards ‘time past’ necessitates the presence of a character who will link the present and the past. Ghulam Mohammad does exactly that by winding back the defunct gramophone to take the audience to the world of classics. The conflict ensues as the present material world interjects its mercantile value systems into the world of classical humanism and innocence. Ghulam with a shake of his hand takes us on a roller coaster ride, riding back and forth into past and present simultaneously as the conflict mentioned before makes its presence felt in Atin’s domestic life. This is established in the form of the tussle between him and his family members who want to refurbish their old house into modern apartments but as per Ghulam’s belief nothing in this world can be completely lost. Everything remains immortal in the aesthetic space of creation. And indeed Atin witnesses his father sitting in the corners of his old house. Roaming from one space to another, Atin ultimately finds the singer’s house and his son, Jibanananda, who has carefully preserved his father’s record till date. The theatrical proficiency doesn’t end here; a layer of mystical meta-theatre is added as Atin’s supposed ‘Other’ comes to visit him often. With the plot somewhat resolving it’s initiated conflicts with the meeting of Atin and Jibananda, Atin hopes to finally meet his ‘Other’. The curtain falls with this awkward expectation evoked.

The older gentleman Ajit is from an old-world background. He is educated, sophisticated and has grown up surrounded by books. He owns a bookstore in College Street of Kolkata, established by his grandfather.The younger woman Maya lives in a Kolkata slum, is not well educated but hungry for knowledge. She joins Ajit’s bookstore as a part time salesgirl. Ajit has certain contempt for her quest for wisdom. He believes that reading is dangerous for somebody who may not understand them, and that people should have an introduction to books and not just be thrown into it. She, on the other hand thinks that books contain all the wisdom in the world.The store does not run well. Ajit is in debt. But, he does not want to change the style of his store.Maya wants to diversify the business, to change the style, even the name of the store. She believes that the responsibility of a bookstore is to reach people with books by any means. She starts changing the business style. The common in both is their loneliness and their passion for books. The two begin to bond and put in an effort to overcome their loneliness.There develops dependence between them. Maya gets a support of his wisdom. Ajit gets traction from her will and energy. Ajit gives his all properties to Maya to make her wishes a success. Surrendering to a terminal ailment, he wishes to survive through the survival of the store. Maya pulls him up from the dejection.They dream to start a journey.DIRECTOR: Amitava DuttaARTISTS Debshankar Halder, Bindiya Ghosh

Mumbai is greatly known as the city that never sleeps. As the scorching sun sets for the day, citizens from all walks of life head out to enjoy the cooler temperature. Marine Drive and other places in close proximity to the sea like Chowpatty are crowded with Mumbaikars enjoying the cool breeze and joyous sunset.In this night tour, you get to the experience the other side of Mumbai. The nightlife out here is never ending. There is always something fun to do or something serene to experience. The Banganga Tank, Jain Temple, the chaotic CST station, and the vibrant shades of cynical sexualism through Mumbai's notorious red light district.Experience the incredible diversity between modern, cosmopolitan and the traditional India.TIME:Operates daily, with the exception of SundayDuration: 2.5 hoursStart Time: 7:00 PMEnd Time: 6:00 PMMEETING LOCATION:Regal Cinema, ColabaTOUR HIGHLIGHTS:CHOWPATTY BEACH: Vibrantly lit up till the wee hours of the morning, Chowpatty beach at night is packed one. Friends and families enjoy drinking juices, licking ice creams and eating Indian snacks.BANGANGA TANK: The water from this famous tank is believed to have special healing powers. Originally built in 1127 the Banganga is surrounded by Hindu temples. Rumor has that its spring comes from the holy Ganges River.JAIN TEMPLE: This intricately-decorated temple is a big tourist attraction because of its vibrancy in colour and its beauty in architecture. The temple signifies peacefulness and non-violence, just like the religion Jainism for which it has been built.KAMALA NEHRU PARK: Malabar Hill is the home of the aristocrats of Mumbai and Kamala Nehru Park is at the heart of it. This park is filled with greenery and creates a peaceful vibe everything you visit it.ANTILIA BUILDING: Get a Sneak Peak street view of the two billion dollar home of business tycoon Mukesh Ambani. As of now, only a street view! :)KAMATHIPURA (RED LIGHT AREA): An area well known but rarely talked about, the Kamathipura district is a land harbouring a torrid affair between man and his sexual desires. Prostitution out in the open, and families torn and broken; these lanes speak of stories with distorted realities and unfavourable outcomes. Witness this reality within the frameworks of your car is strongly advised!CST STATION: One of the busiest railway stations in the country, Chatrapathi Shivaji Terminus is a beautifully designed station of British architecture. It is also the same station that was under 24/11 Terrorist attacks in 2008. The award-winning movie "Slumdog Millionaire" was also shot here. This grand site is gloriously lit up in the evening and you will enjoy this view at the end of the tour.

A magical blend of traditional Tamil harvest festival and modern rock & folk melodies, the International Pongal Festival is a truly unique party experience. The International Pongal Festival aims to bring the traditional and modern together. While you dance through the night in paradise and sway to the Indian melodies, you will find yourself in the ancient Tamil Nadu while experiencing a post-modern experience with rock bands under the lights of fireworks. Get ready to be mesmerized by the beauty of Indian folk dances while trying exquisite examples of delicious Tamil Nadu cuisine. When you are done with such calming activities as flower arranging and mimicry, fireeaters and cricket players will boost your adrenaline. Moreover, there will be a lot of workshops to turn you into a perfect Tamil Nadu local. Don't forget to learn your fortune before you leave the beautiful concert venue. Well, we can also tell your fortune: You'll attend the International Pongal Festival in 2017 as well. Get your tickets here! http://www.pongalfest.com/tickets

event_name: Trekगुरु : Backpack Trip To Srinagar - Leh - Ladakh - Manali On 13-24/08/16
description: Trekगुरु : Backpack Trip To Srinagar - Leh - Ladakh - Manali Date : 13 Aug (Saturday) to 24 Aug (Wednesday) 2016 Duration : 11 nights / 12 days (Srinagar to Chandigadh) Height : Max 5328 mtrs (17582 ft) Cost : Rs.27,000 (Ex-Srinagar to Manali) Non-refundable advance: Rs.10,000 Flight/Train ticket charges (optional) Contact : PRAVIN 9821318848/9821465256/7039253983 ---------- Highlights : Houseboat -Shikara - Dal lake - Sonamarg - Drass & Zojila Pass - Kargil War Memorial - Magnetic Hill - Leh - Shanti stupa - Khardungla Pass- Nubra valley - Pengong Lake - Sarchu - Manali City- Chandigadh ---------- Srinagar is Situated at the center of the Kashmir valley, Srinagar is the second most populous district in the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir, after Jammu District and is home to the summer capital (Srinagar) of Jammu and Kashmir (The capital moves to Jammu city in the winter). The largest city is Srinagar. Leh is situated roughly between 32 to 36 degree north Latitude and 75 to 80 degree East longitude and altitude ranging from 2300 mtrs to 5000 mtrs above sea level. District Leh with and area of 45100 Sq. Kms. makes it one of the largest District in the country.The District is bounded by Pakistan occupied Kashmir in the west and China in the North and eastern part and Lahul Spiti of Himachal Pardesh in the south east. It is at a distance of 434 Kms from State capital ( Summer) Srinagar and 474 Kms from Manali (HP). Topographically, the whole of the district is mountainous with three parallel ranges of the Himalayas, the Zanskar, the Ladakh and the Karakoram. Between these ranges, the Shayok, Indus and Zanskar rivers flow and most of the population lives in valleys of these rivers. Manali is surrounded by high peaks in the beautiful green valley of the Beas River, with mountain adventures beckoning from all directions, Manali is a year-round magnet. Backpackers come to hang out in the hippie villages around the main town; adventurers come for trekking, climbing, mountain biking, canyoning, paragliding, rafting and skiing; and Indian families and honeymooners come for the cool mountain air and a taste of snow on a day trip to the Rohtang La. ---------- Itinerary & Trip Detail : Day 01: Saturday 13/08/2016 : Mumbai To Srinagar - Arrival at Srinagar Airport and transfer to the houseboat for relaxation and acclimatisation Lunch Visit Shankaracharya Temple & Moghal Garden Shikara Ride at Dal Lake Dinner Overnight Houseboat Day 02: Sunday 14/08/2016 : Srinagar to Kargil (250 Kms / 8 Hrs)Sonamarg : Drass Village : Kargil After Breakfast drive towards Kargil via Sonamarg (Known as Gateway to Ladakh) Drass & Zojila Pass Arrival at Hotel Overnight at Kargil Day 03: Monday 15/08/2016 : Kargil to Leh Via Lamayuru (285 Kms / 9 Hrs) After Breakfast celebrate Independence day with Indian Army at Kargil War Memorial, Inroute Visit Lamayuru Gompa , Alchi Gompa & If Possible Likir Gompa, Magnetic Hill Overnight at Leh Day 04: Thuesday 16/08/2016 : Leh At Leh a complete 1/2 day of rest. After lunch visit Leh Market, Leh Palace, Hall of Fame and Shanti Stupa Day 05: Wednesday 17/08/2017 : Leh to Nubra Valley (120 Kms) Nubra Valley via Khardungla Arrive at Deskit by Afternoon. Rest of the day one is free to explore Deskit, Hunder Villages and camel Safari in Sand Dunes Dinner & Overnight at Camp Day 06: Thursday 18/08/2016 : Nubra Valley to Leh (120 Kms) Visit Deskit Monastery from where you can have an excellent view of the confluence of Shayok and Siachan rivers. drive back to Leh by same Route, crossing Khardungla Pass Dinner & Ovetnight at Hotel Day 07: Friday 19/08/2016 : Leh to Pangong Lake (160 Kms)Pangong Lake 14,500 ft, through Changla Pass 17,350 ft. An early morning drive is recommended, on the way visit Thiksay monastery puja around 6:30 am, enjoy the view of the Chemray monastery and cross Changa pass, enroute Tangtsay village and we reach to Pangong. Enjoy hot luch and walk around the lake. Dinner & Overnight stay at Camp Day 08: Saturday 20/08/2016 : Pangong Lake to Leh (160 Kms) Back to Leh, but one should not miss the early morning raising sunshine of the lake and its beautiful birds singing, enroute visit Hemis, Thikse Monastery and Shey Palace.& Sindhu Darshan Dinner & Overnight at Hotel Day 09: Sunday 21/08/2016 : Leh To Sarchu (250 Km.) Sarchu Via Karu Upsi Rumtse Tanglang-La-Pass(17582 ft) Debring Pang Lachung-La Pass (Around 15500 ft) Nakee-La- Pass (Around 15000 fr) Arrive at Sarchu by evening. Overnight stay follows in the Camp. Day 10: Monday 22/08/2016 : Sarchu To Manali (225 Km.) Baralacha-La-Pass (15000 ft) Zing Zingbar Darcha Jispa Keylong Kokhsar Rohatang Pass(13500 ft) to Manali Dinner & Overnight at Hotel Day 11: Thuesday 23/08/2016 : Manali To Chandigarh (275 Km. 7 - 8 hrs one way Approx) Visit Around Manali Hidimba Mata Temple Vasishth Rishi Temple Afternoon Take Volvo Bus To Chandigadh Day 12: Wednesday 24/08/2016 : Chandigadh To Mumbai ---------- Cost : Rs.27,000 (Ex- Srinagar to Manali) Non-refundable advance: Rs.10,000 Flight/Train ticket charges (optional) ---------- Includes: Virtually all expenses from Srinagar to Manali (except lunch) 11 days breakfast, dinner, tea and refreshments 11 days accommodation expenses 2/3/4 sharing Travel expenses in bus or jeep during trip Entry charges at various monasteries, national park or other places Local Guide Charges Trekगुरु Charges ---------- Excludes: Dinner and next morning breakfast while travelling in bus from Manali to Chandigadh Lunch is not included throughout the tour. Personal orders of cold drink, mineral water, snacks, etc. Medical cost, if any Any exotic or expensive food. You are expected to pay for anything which is not included in the criteria of “simple food and accommodation”. anything not mentioned in the Includes --------- Contact : PRAVIN 9821318848/9821465256/7039253983 ---------- To confirm his/her registration needs to deposit Advance payment (10,000rs) into the following bank account (Please write your name in description) Account Details : Bank Name: BANK OF MAHARASHTRA Account ID: 20059830445 Account Type: Savings Bank Account Account name: PRAVIN P. KAMBLE Branch: BHOIWADA - MUMBAI IFSC code: MAHB0000563 ********** Do's, Dont's & Facts:- - Kindly carry 1 Identity proof - This is a backpack trip. We will choose place of accommodation based on group’s opinion and the expertise of group leader. - Our daily schedule during trip may differ from our usual daily life schedule with respect to day chores, tea timing, food timing etc. Please don’t complain about these petty issues. - On most of the days we will wake up early to travel comfortably and enjoy the serenity of morning. Early to bed, early to rise will be followed particularly on the days of trek. - Always respect the local people and their culture. We try to learn more from them about the place. - Since it is a backpack trip, you are expected to proactively involve in helping the team. - Cost Not Included Insurance, medical Coverage. - Please do not carry or wear any valuables, ornaments, jewellery, etc. If carried, then we Do Not take any liability for the same. - It is most essential to be fit and fine before heading for trekking. While planning your trekking trip, it is preferable to have a medical fitness check-up done. - Rock Climbing, Rappelling, Trekking or any adventure activity is potentially risky. For all these events you are at your own risk. - All activities & programs carry an amount of risk of injury and you are aware that outdoor activities have an inherent risk of personal injury. - Organizers are not responsible for any accident, mishap (including death) or compensation in whatsoever manner. - Trekगुरु reserves all right to change/deviate/cancel the plans without any prior notice. - Smoking and alcohol strictly prohibited. - Be a group - its not a race. - NO littering please...we are educated. - Any adventure activity is a disciplined fun. - The leader’s decision will be final and binding on all members. No Arguments will be entertained. Sometimes we may need to adjust as per the opinion of others. - Read the event itinerary at least once. ---------- ----------SEFETY FIRST---------- -------------Save Water-------------

PLEASE READ THIS BEAUTIFUL STORY..... My mom only had one eye. I hated her… She was such an embarrassment. She cooked for students and teachers to support the family. There was this one day during elementary school where my mom came to say hello to me. I was so embarrassed. How could she do this to me? I ignored her, threw her a hateful look and ran out. The next day at school one of my classmates said, ‘EEEE, your mom only has one eye!’ I wanted to bury myself. I also wanted my mom to just disappear. I confronted her that day and said, "If you’re only gonna make me a laughing stock, why don't you just die?" My mom did not respond… I didn’t even stop to think for a second about what I had said, because I was full of anger. I was oblivious to her feelings. I wanted out of that house, and have nothing to do with her. So I studied real hard, got a chance to go abroad to study. Then, I got married. I bought a house of my own. I had kids of my own. I was happy with my life, my kids and the comforts. Then one day, my Mother came to visit me. She hadn’t seen me in years and she didn’t even meet her grandchildren. When she stood by the door, my children laughed at her, and I yelled at her for coming over uninvited. I screamed at her, "How dare you come to my house and scare my children! GET OUT OF HERE! NOW!!!" And to this, my mother quietly answered, "Oh, I’m so sorry. I may have gotten the wrong address," and she disappeared out of sight. One day, a letter regarding a school reunion came to my house. So I lied to my wife that I was going on a business trip. After the reunion, I went to the old shack just out of curiosity. My neighbors said that she died. I did not shed a single tear. They handed me a letter that she had wanted me to have. "My dearest son, I think of you all the time. I’m sorry that I came to your house and scared your children. I was so glad when I heard you were coming for the reunion. But I may not be able to even get out of bed to see you. I’m sorry that I was a constant embarrassment to you when you were growing up. You see…….. when you were very little, you got into an accident, and lost your eye. As a mother, I couldn’t stand watching you having to grow up with one eye. So I gave you mine. I was so proud of my son who was seeing a whole new world for me, in my place, with that eye. With all my love to you, Your mother." The son got into tears, but it was too late. MORAL LESSON: Never neglet your MuM, Because she is a blessing. One day you will cry when she will be gone.... event_name: World Music Day Concert 2016 - Bombay Meri Jaan
description: Sourendro Soumyajit's Bombay Meri Jaan, a world music concert. If Life is stranger than fiction ; Bollywood is larger than life. Conceived on the real-life story, struggle, journey, ups-and-downs of producers, music-directors, aspiring singers, lyricists – this Broadway style musical talks of legends in the making. . Young singers plays the role of the greats from the industry. So we get to see a real Kishore Kumar once more chatting his heart out with RD Burman, hear Madanmohan guide Lata Mangeshkar, enjoy Mohd rafi dancing his voice to steps of Shammi ‘elvis’ Kapoor, Yo-yo honey singh going gaga. Dada Sahab Phalke to New Theatres to today’s digital base cinematograph – where Indian cinema is the most talked about industry in world entertainment scenario, this Broadway style musical, packed with heights of stagecraft, live music, choreography, is a historic journey of every turning point of this sagaA 120 minute spectacle of stagecraft – presented by 100 artists.

A Celebration of the Free Spirit called Motorcycling....MotoDay has been conceived to be an equal platform for all two wheels; be it any make kind or creed. Motorcycling is the ultimate equalizer; a lot of people have been riding and keeping the spirit of riding alive on individual levels; MotoDay is an effort to create a platform in bringing all riders to a common platform without any pre-requisites and any pre-set notion. MotoDay is also conceived to provide a platform to motorcycling related start-ups which have been “Of the riders, For the Riders, By the Riders”.On June 21st every year is celebrated as the world motorcycle day throughout the world, as a pre-cursor to this occasion we bring to you MotoDay 2016. This event is about the celebration of the free spirit and the passion for motorcycling. The event last year had 1700 + like minded bikers converging at the venue for the event. event_name: Rustic Rajasthan - Photography Escape For Jaipurites
description: All inclusive pocket friendly escape for those who love photography and want to capture the cultural art of Rajasthan into there camera. Package Price: 2500/- per person only Inclusions: * Return train tickets from Jaipur * Room on sharing basis for 02 nights * All meals * Sightseeing & excursions * All local transport Limited seats! Day 1 - Travel from Jaipur to Falna in train. Check-in at The Country Retreat Farmstay, a boutique farmstay on 130 acres of farm estate near Ranakpur. Post lunch enjoy Jeep ride into the rural countryside along with visit to Malinath Cave Temple which is indeed a wonder to witness! Placed over a height of 350 steps, the temple is carved out in a splendid cave. Once on top, you will witness a beautiful skyline - A spectacle for the shutterbugs. Return to the farm to capture the setting sun in your camera. In night experience an unique farm wildlife safari in the rough farm fields in an open jeep to spot antelopes along with other wild creatures. Day 2 - Start your day with a opportunity to witness breathtaking sunrise at farm. After breakfast leave for excursion to world famous Ranakpur Jain Temple, an architectural wonder with 1444 carved pillars. Post lunch trek to nearby lake in Ranakpur for some landscape photography along with spotting crocodiles and birds around the lake. Return to farm in the evening. The unpolluted sky glitters with twinkling stars. Don't miss the shooting stars. While on this trip experience the rustic charm of Rajasthan. The Godwar region of Rajasthan is full of cultural heritage, offering an enormous scope of photography with a wide range from the charming landscape to the famed Shepard community - Raika Rebari. Day 3 - Post breakfast board train for Jaipur.
